entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued February 17 at 6:16AM EST by NWS Greenville-Spartanburg SC
entry.summary: A mix of snow, sleet, and light freezing rain or freezing drizzle will fall across the North Carolina mountains this morning, especially at the higher elevations and in locations near the Tennessee border. Snow accumulations will be light, with mostly one-half inch or less on grassy surfaces, except for 1 to 2 inches possible along the higher ridges. Any spotty ice accretion will be mainly on elevated surfaces. However, temperatures falling into the 20s in many locations this morning may cause patchy black ice to form on area roadways. Slippery road conditions could result through noon, or perhaps into the early afternoon. The wintry precipitation will taper off this afternoon.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued February 16 at 3:08PM MST by NWS Albuquerque NM
entry.summary: A moist backdoor cold front will dive into the area late tonight ushering freezing drizzle and freezing fog into much of east central and northeast New Mexico. The hazardous conditions are forecast to linger through Saturday morning, while freezing fog expands to the east slopes of the south central mountains including Ruidoso and Duncan. Light ice accumulations up to 0.05 of an inch are expected mainly along and east of a line from Raton to Las Vegas and Clines Corners, including the I-25 and I-40 corridors. These amounts will likely result in slick travel conditions in some areas, especially on bridges and overpasses. In addition, visibilities less than a quarter mile will be possible at times. As of this writing, conditions do not look to be as bad along and south of a line from Clovis to Roswell, but that could change depending on how far south the better moisture plunges. Motorists should consider alternate routes or travel times, and monitor the latest forecasts, statements, advisories, and warnings, to avoid being impacted by this hazardous winter weather event.
